#: src/pages/docs/DevicesHelpPage.tsx:140
msgid "A device's streams become ordinary managed Sources, and its decode slots become ordinary managed Outputs, each carrying a <0>device_ref</0> annotation in its body. The engine's ingest and serving paths are untouched — the binding only tells the driver which device the resource belongs to (and blocks deleting the device while something still references it). Where a vendor does not document a stream URL, the UI flags the candidate as unverified and you supply the URL yourself — it is never silently guessed."
msgstr "A device's streams become ordinary managed Sources, and its decode slots become ordinary managed Outputs, each carrying a <0>device_ref</0> annotation in its body. The engine's ingest and serving paths are untouched — the binding only tells the driver which device the resource belongs to (and blocks deleting the device while something still references it). Where a vendor does not document a stream URL, the UI flags the candidate as unverified and you supply the URL yourself — it is never silently guessed."

#: src/pages/docs/DevicesAdoptHelpPage.tsx:29
msgid "A discovery scan browses the network (mDNS/DNS-SD) for a bounded few seconds and lists what answered. Anything on the network can answer a broadcast, so the results are an untrusted inventory of hints: they are not devices, they carry no credentials, and Multiview never adopts them automatically. Every adoption is an explicit operator confirmation — the row's Adopt button only prefills the dialog; nothing exists until you confirm it."
msgstr "A discovery scan browses the network (mDNS/DNS-SD) for a bounded few seconds and lists what answered. Anything on the network can answer a broadcast, so the results are an untrusted inventory of hints: they are not devices, they carry no credentials, and Multiview never adopts them automatically. Every adoption is an explicit operator confirmation — the row's Adopt button only prefills the dialog; nothing exists until you confirm it."

#: src/pages/docs/DisplayNodesHelpPage.tsx:28
msgid "A display node is a single-board computer or spare PC running Multiview's node software, driving one or more physical displays. Nodes are adopted as managed devices with the <0>displaynode</0> driver and present the program, a declared output, or one head of a video wall. Because the node software is ours end-to-end, display nodes reach the frame-accurate sync tier — every head of a wall shows the same frame index."
msgstr "A display node is a single-board computer or spare PC running Multiview's node software, driving one or more physical displays. Nodes are adopted as managed devices with the <0>displaynode</0> driver and present the program, a declared output, or one head of a video wall. Because the node software is ours end-to-end, display nodes reach the frame-accurate sync tier — every head of a wall shows the same frame index."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TransportsPage.tsx:309
msgid "A feed crossing the internet: SRT (tune the latency window to the link)."
msgstr "A feed crossing the internet: SRT (tune the latency window to the link)."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TransportsPage.tsx:199
msgid "A file source plays media from disk, paced to real time so it behaves like a live feed on the wall (and can loop). Synthetic sources — color bars, solid fills, and a ticking clock — are generated in-process with no network or decode at all. They are ideal for layout work, burn-in tests, and proving the output path end to end before any real feed is connected."
msgstr "A file source plays media from disk, paced to real time so it behaves like a live feed on the wall (and can loop). Synthetic sources — color bars, solid fills, and a ticking clock — are generated in-process with no network or decode at all. They are ideal for layout work, burn-in tests, and proving the output path end to end before any real feed is connected."

#: src/layout/components/GridLayoutEditor.tsx:288
msgid "A grid layout places cells by named areas on column/row tracks — resize whole rows and columns at once, with even gaps."
msgstr "A grid layout places cells by named areas on column/row tracks — resize whole rows and columns at once, with even gaps."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:27
msgid "A layout decides where every tile sits on the canvas. Use a factory preset (such as 2x2 or 1+5), a CSS-grid with named areas and fractional tracks, or absolute normalized rectangles for full control. A cell's fit mode controls how a source is scaled into its tile — contain to letterbox, cover to crop and fill, or fill to stretch."
msgstr "A layout decides where every tile sits on the canvas. Use a factory preset (such as 2x2 or 1+5), a CSS-grid with named areas and fractional tracks, or absolute normalized rectangles for full control. A cell's fit mode controls how a source is scaled into its tile — contain to letterbox, cover to crop and fill, or fill to stretch."

#: src/layout/components/validationMessages.tsx:19
msgid "A layout name is required."
msgstr "A layout name is required."

